There's a lot of things that go into the regular furry fandom's popularity.
At the absolute baseline it's pretty much the same as ours—interest in anthropomorphized animal people to some extent. Despite that, with furries there's a whole rabbit hole of garbage that piles up to make them what they are. Self loathing, perversion, narcissism, desire for popularity, and desperation to feel like part of a community, just to name a few. Another part is that they've existed for a lot longer. Some might say that we're closer to the original furries, but ultimately that doesn't really matter as the modern furries are the ones who own the claim to the furry fandom.
Their interest in anthropomorphic animals is simultaneously skin deep and all encompassing. They fully embrace it as themselves and make it a core piece of their personality, but they also have little regard for meaningful discussion, ideas, or theories regarding such things. That's not to say they don't, quite the opposite, but that they attempt to force those things to adhere to themselves rather than attempting to logically follow from real things. This is why so often their depictions of anthros can easily be boiled down to "humans with fur". Here we go into lengthy discussions as to how different animals strengths, weaknesses, and individual quirks would play a role in anthros versions of said animals. They, on the other hand, frequently depict anthros exclusively with those features that are non-intrusive on life in civilization. They refuse to entertain the idea that some animals would struggle to do things we find completely mundane. This is why they typically depict anthros as sweating and having human hands and feet.
I'm sure you could easily write an entire thesis on furries, the hmofa crowd, and the differences between the two, but this is just a simple overview.
